<Author>VonderHogl
<Content>A Few Improvements Still Needed The Adler is a small hotel situated in a busy residential neighborhood. It is not close to the usual attractions of Madrid, but these can be reached fairly quickly by taxi or underground service. I actually grew to like the area as it is an older yet very upscale part of Madrid with most buildings, though dating from the mid to late 1800s, being quite well maintained and rather 'regal' in appearanceMy room was a corner room with windows facing the main street -- therefore, it was a bit noisy. The fittings in the room were acceptable, though not quite as modern as I'd like for a hotel in this category. For instance, the shower was not separate from the bathtub and the curtain didn't close properly, which meant the floor was covered with water after each shower. Internet service was bizarre; the wired service didn't work at all and the wireless only worked when I sat at the door with the computer on my lap. The bed was too firm for my liking and the duvet too thick. The room was dark enough for a good sleep; only the noise and hard bed kept me awake! Toiletries were by Etro and the housekeeping was immaculate -- one lady even wrote me a poem one morning and placed it on my pillow with a few flower petals.Other than housekeeping, service was generally poor. Other than one ebullient concierge, the rest were either ignorant of English or simply didn't wish to speak it (a frequent lament I have when traveling to 5-star properties in Spain). In fact, I would call one of these fellows downright rude and unhelpful. The restaurant is small and cozy, but service there also lacked charm. Again, basic items became complications for the service crew owing to their lack of command of English. One evening I waited at the bar for 15 minutes and no one ever arrived to serve -- even though I inquired three times at the front desk.This hotel has potential. It's intimate and downright cozy at times. However, the service needs to lighten up and smile ... and put a little 'step' into its pace. 
